  <main>
    <!-- Pushing Section -->
    <section id="pushing">
      <h2>Pushing</h2>
      <p>
        Pushing in SourceTree means sending your local commits to the remote repository. This updates the remote with your changes and makes them available to your team.
      </p>
      <h3>Steps to Push Your Changes:</h3>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Open Your Repository:</strong> Launch SourceTree and open the repository you wish to work on.</li>
        <li><strong>Stage Changes:</strong> Review and select the modified files to stage them for commit.</li>
        <li><strong>Commit:</strong> Enter a descriptive commit message that explains your changes, then click the <em>Commit</em> button to record your changes locally.</li>
        <li><strong>Initiate Push:</strong> Click the <em>Push</em> button in the toolbar.</li>
        <li><strong>Review & Confirm:</strong> Verify that the correct branch is selected in the push dialog, then confirm by clicking <em>Push</em> to update the remote repository.</li>
      </ol>
    </section>
    
    <!-- Pulling Section -->
    <section id="pulling">
      <h2>Pulling</h2>
      <p>
        Pulling in SourceTree is the process of fetching and merging changes from the remote repository into your local branch. This ensures your local repository is up-to-date with the teamâ€™s work.
      </p>
      <h3>Steps to Pull Remote Changes:</h3>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Open Your Repository:</strong> Launch SourceTree and navigate to your desired repository.</li>
        <li><strong>Initiate Pull:</strong> Click the <em>Pull</em> button on the toolbar.</li>
        <li><strong>Select Remote Branch:</strong> Choose the correct remote branch in the pull dialog.</li>
        <li><strong>Execute Pull:</strong> Click <em>OK</em> or <em>Pull</em> to fetch and merge remote changes into your local branch.</li>
        <li><strong>Resolve Conflicts:</strong> If merge conflicts arise, use SourceTree's conflict resolution tools to fix them before completing the pull.</li>
      </ol>
    </section>
    
    <!-- Synchronization Section -->
    <section id="sync">
      <h2>Synchronization</h2>
      <p>
        Synchronization in SourceTree combines both pulling remote changes and pushing your local commits. This process keeps your local and remote repositories in sync.
      </p>
      <h3>Steps to Synchronize Your Repository:</h3>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Open Your Repository:</strong> Launch SourceTree and open your repository.</li>
        <li><strong>Access the Sync View:</strong> Click the <em>Sync</em> (or <em>Pull/Push</em>) button in the toolbar to view incoming and outgoing commits.</li>
        <li><strong>Pull Changes:</strong> First, pull the latest changes from the remote repository to ensure your local copy is up-to-date.</li>
        <li><strong>Push Local Commits:</strong> Once your local repository is updated, push your commits by clicking the <em>Push</em> button within the sync view.</li>
        <li><strong>Confirm Synchronization:</strong> Verify that both your local and remote repositories display the same commit history.</li>
      </ol>
    </section>
  </main>
  
